00:04:43.310 --> 00:04:45.420
So why XServe?

00:04:45.420 --> 00:04:47.700
Well, again, you know,
we really think with XServe

00:04:47.700 --> 00:04:50.780
we've really kind of broken the
mold of servers in this space.

00:04:50.800 --> 00:04:54.090
Really bringing a great
mix of processing power,

00:04:54.120 --> 00:04:59.050
networking, IO, storage,
all into a phenomenal 1U form

00:04:59.110 --> 00:05:03.630
factor with great value and great
capabilities of Mac OS X Server.

00:05:03.800 --> 00:05:06.920
And again, the G5 really has

00:05:07.160 --> 00:05:12.740
raise the bar in capabilities for Xserve,
really bringing 64-bit computing

00:05:12.760 --> 00:05:17.280
power that we're continuing to
tap into with Mac OS X Server.

00:05:17.280 --> 00:05:19.410
And a phenomenal architecture.

00:05:19.410 --> 00:05:22.210
With Xserve G5,
we've really redesigned the

00:05:22.260 --> 00:05:26.200
architecture inside the box to
really bring higher throughput,

00:05:26.200 --> 00:05:28.620
higher bandwidth into the system.

00:05:28.620 --> 00:05:30.470
It's not just about the G5 processor.

00:05:30.470 --> 00:05:34.550
It's about more memory bandwidth,
ECC memory capabilities,

00:05:34.550 --> 00:05:37.500
PCIX capabilities,
serial ATA hard drives,

00:05:37.500 --> 00:05:39.620
phenomenal networking bandwidth.

00:05:39.620 --> 00:05:43.180
And not just bandwidth,
but new features like VLAN capability

00:05:43.180 --> 00:05:47.380
and more hardware checksumming
capabilities in the chipset itself.

00:05:47.380 --> 00:05:50.300
Just really bringing a
really server-based approach

00:05:50.300 --> 00:05:51.880
into this architecture.

00:05:53.800 --> 00:05:56.720
and other really important fact and
we'll touch on this a little bit

00:05:56.740 --> 00:06:00.190
more in the planning segment but

00:06:00.380 --> 00:06:02.390
With the G5,
we really have a great advantage

00:06:02.390 --> 00:06:05.550
in that for the processor,
the amount of power and heat

00:06:05.640 --> 00:06:08.100
that it outputs is significantly
lower than the competition.

00:06:08.100 --> 00:06:12.000
And, you know, I like to joke,
you can put an Xserve anywhere.

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:14.070
You can put it in your office,
you can put it on a shelf,

00:06:14.070 --> 00:06:16.960
you can put it really a single
Xserve just about anywhere.

00:06:16.960 --> 00:06:20.000
But when you start putting
several of these on a single

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:23.780
power circuit in an enclosed room,
you start to have to really begin

00:06:23.830 --> 00:06:28.060
to factor out into your equation
the environmental impacts of that.

00:06:28.500 --> 00:06:32.170
I had a couple extra servers in my
office over the weekend planning for

00:06:32.170 --> 00:06:35.500
some of the demos in this session,
and I had my door all closed up.

00:06:35.500 --> 00:06:39.100
Coming in over the weekend,
the room was quite warm.

00:06:39.100 --> 00:06:42.480
It just wasn't built for the kind
of cooling that's required to move

00:06:42.480 --> 00:06:44.500
air through this number of machines.

00:06:44.500 --> 00:06:48.500
And that's just with the lower
power and heat output of Xserve.

00:06:48.500 --> 00:06:51.690
I also want to take a moment to
really comment on the thermal

00:06:51.690 --> 00:06:53.470
design of the architecture.

00:06:53.500 --> 00:06:55.880
This is something we take when
we design these systems very,

00:06:55.880 --> 00:06:56.700
very seriously.

00:06:56.700 --> 00:06:59.420
This is a very,
very rigorous design in the

00:06:59.420 --> 00:07:01.700
thermal and the cooling system.

00:07:01.700 --> 00:07:03.700
We're very much purist in this respect.

00:07:03.700 --> 00:07:07.540
It's a pure front-to-back airflow,
very intelligently

00:07:07.540 --> 00:07:09.620
monitored fans and systems.

00:07:09.790 --> 00:07:13.030
We're leveraging the same technology
that was first introduced in the

00:07:13.030 --> 00:07:16.700
Power Mac G5 with intelligent thermal
monitoring with thermal zones.

00:07:16.700 --> 00:07:19.000
And while we don't have
independent thermal zones,

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:21.890
we have a tremendous amount of
monitoring and data coming off this

00:07:21.890 --> 00:07:24.900
logic board to be able to control
how fast the fans should move.

00:07:24.900 --> 00:07:24.900
And we're very much
purist in this respect.

00:07:24.900 --> 00:07:24.900
It's a pure front-to-back airflow,
very intelligently

00:07:24.900 --> 00:07:24.900
monitored fans and systems.

