We're leveraging the same technology
that was first introduced in the

00:07:24.900 --> 00:07:24.900
Power Mac G5 with intelligent thermal
monitoring with thermal zones.

00:07:24.900 --> 00:07:24.900
And while we don't have
independent thermal zones,

00:07:24.900 --> 00:07:24.900
we have a tremendous amount of
monitoring and data coming off this

00:07:24.900 --> 00:07:24.900
logic board to be able to control
how fast the fans should move.

00:07:24.900 --> 00:07:29.450
should run and make sure
everything's cooled to optimum

00:07:29.470 --> 00:07:32.040
efficiency for best performance.

00:07:32.040 --> 00:07:35.510
If you heard a customer comment
in one of the HPC sections,

00:07:35.510 --> 00:07:38.110
who just installed a
cluster of 64 machines,

00:07:38.110 --> 00:07:40.380
when he first came into the room,
he thought, "Oh, my God,

00:07:40.380 --> 00:07:43.250
these things were really loud," and it
turned out there were two Dell servers

00:07:43.250 --> 00:07:45.240
in the corner that he left on.

00:07:45.240 --> 00:07:50.940
Turning them off, it was much quieter,
and that was a 64-machine cluster.

00:07:50.940 --> 00:07:54.410
So we're pretty pleased that
for the power and air that we're

00:07:54.630 --> 00:07:58.160
moving through this machine,
it is as quiet, if not quieter,

00:07:58.180 --> 00:07:59.830
than the slot-load G4.

00:08:01.390 --> 00:08:03.300
This is a look at power efficiency.

00:08:03.300 --> 00:08:07.460
And this, again,
is a huge advantage as we look at this.

00:08:07.460 --> 00:08:12.160
The processor in the XServe G5
is spec'd at about 55 watts.

00:08:12.170 --> 00:08:15.850
So as we look at competing processors,
we see literally twice the power

00:08:15.850 --> 00:08:18.140
performance going through those systems.

00:08:18.140 --> 00:08:20.220
And more power means more cost.

00:08:20.220 --> 00:08:22.360
You've got to pay for that power.

00:08:22.360 --> 00:08:24.460
It means more cooling required.

00:08:24.580 --> 00:08:27.370
You've got to pull the
heat out of the room.

00:08:27.370 --> 00:08:32.650
And kind of the corollary to thermal,
the heat of the system,

00:08:32.650 --> 00:08:35.850
is reliability because thermal
management goes directly into

00:08:35.850 --> 00:08:38.610
the reliability of the system.

00:08:39.780 --> 00:08:43.300
Another thing about the XServe G5 is
one of the key differentiators about the

00:08:43.300 --> 00:08:47.800
XServe is that this system is designed
from the ground up as a server platform.

00:08:47.800 --> 00:08:50.900
And that means not only really
striving at not just processor

00:08:50.900 --> 00:08:53.500
performance but IO performance,
but it also means

00:08:53.500 --> 00:08:54.900
monitoring and management.

00:08:54.900 --> 00:08:57.420
And with XServe,
I like to joke it's one of the most

00:08:57.420 --> 00:08:59.820
instrumented 1U servers in the industry.

00:08:59.820 --> 00:09:02.640
We have, last count,
I think it was 38 sensors

00:09:02.640 --> 00:09:06.050
on the logic board,
including 10 temperature sensors,

00:09:06.120 --> 00:09:08.650
8 fan sensors,
voltage and current sensors

00:09:08.650 --> 00:09:10.250
throughout the system.

00:09:10.260 --> 00:09:13.280
We're literally monitoring
temperature of the incoming ambient

00:09:13.370 --> 00:09:15.260
air through the front of the machine.

00:09:15.260 --> 00:09:17.360
We're measuring the
processor temperature,

00:09:17.360 --> 00:09:19.610
the core temperature,
the memory temperature,

00:09:19.610 --> 00:09:22.220
the power supply temperature,
the PCI temperature,

00:09:22.220 --> 00:09:24.940
which gives you outgoing
air temperature as well.

00:09:24.940 --> 00:09:28.360
It's just a very well monitored server,
and it gives you a lot of insight.

00:09:28.780 --> 00:09:30.840
Not only into how the
server itself is running,

00:09:30.890 --> 00:09:33.350
but the general air flow
in your server environment.

00:09:33.360 --> 00:09:36.560
If the ambient air alone is
coming in and is too warm,

00:09:36.560 --> 00:09:40.460
you're going to know right away
there's an air flow situation,

00:09:40.460 --> 00:09:44.970
cooling situations in your data center.

00:09:45.120 --> 00:09:48.720
And of course this data is wrapped
up into our monitoring tools.

00:09:48.720 --> 00:09:52.330
Server Monitor really providing
point and click access into the data

00:09:52.330 --> 00:09:56.660
coming off of XServe G5 and able
to monitor one or multiple servers,

00:09:56.700 --> 00:09:59.590
get email alerts, kind of the quick look.

00:09:59.600 --> 00:10:01.440
Green is good,
yellow is a warning condition,

00:10:01.440 --> 00:10:03.760
red's an error condition.

00:10:03.800 --> 00:10:06.180
Being able to take advantage of
things like smart technology,

00:10:06.180 --> 00:10:09.910
being able to do pre-failure
analysis on the hard drives is

00:10:09.910 --> 00:10:12.900
a key feature in Server Monitor.

00:10:13.060 --> 00:10:16.710
We've enriched Server Monitor quite
a bit with the new data that we're

00:10:16.990 --> 00:10:18.980
now capturing off the XServe G5.

00:10:18.980 --> 00:10:22.600
So for example, one of the new tabs in
Server Monitor is the memory tab,

00:10:22.600 --> 00:10:27.320
which provides detailed error
reporting on ECC error counts.

00:10:27.370 --> 00:10:30.200
And we actually provide that
information by individual DIMM.

00:10:30.210 --> 00:10:34.090
So you can actually see what individual
DIMM might be flagging ECC errors,

00:10:34.090 --> 00:10:35.850
should you see any.

