And of course, Xserve of course comes
with Mac OS X Server.

00:10:40.600 --> 00:10:43.370
So right out of the box,
unlimited client license and

00:10:43.370 --> 00:10:46.140
our server configuration,
a broad range of server

00:10:46.140 --> 00:10:48.040
services right out of the box.

00:10:48.040 --> 00:10:53.710
Been able to handle a vast majority
of traditional server capabilities

00:10:53.910 --> 00:10:56.290
with everything you need.

00:10:56.960 --> 00:11:00.760
and of course with Tiger coming
we have new capabilities that are

00:11:00.760 --> 00:11:02.140
being brought to the platform.

00:11:02.140 --> 00:11:05.350
And of course you've heard all this
week about Tiger so I'm not going to

00:11:05.410 --> 00:11:07.040
need to go into any more of it here.

00:11:07.040 --> 00:11:09.770
But I will highlight one or two key
features that I think is going to

00:11:09.770 --> 00:11:14.490
be useful as we look forward with
Xserve deployment with Tiger server.

00:11:14.720 --> 00:11:17.220
So let's go into a little
bit about planning,

00:11:17.220 --> 00:11:19.900
a little about some of the key
things that should be of concern when

00:11:19.900 --> 00:11:23.940
you're looking at deploying Xserves,
even before you start kind of screwing

00:11:23.940 --> 00:11:26.980
and gluing the machines together and
connecting them up to your network.

00:11:26.980 --> 00:11:32.510
So the first thing I want to
touch on is physical requirements.

00:11:32.980 --> 00:11:35.870
Being a rack-based system,
there are different things that

00:11:35.870 --> 00:11:38.700
should be accounted for and
things that can be looked at.

00:11:38.700 --> 00:11:39.710
So let's start with that.

00:11:39.720 --> 00:11:42.570
So racking is probably one
of the most basic things,

00:11:42.660 --> 00:11:45.760
probably one of the things
you might take for granted,

00:11:45.760 --> 00:11:49.270
but it's kind of interesting
to look at some Xserve in

00:11:49.280 --> 00:11:51.460
the scope of industry trends.

00:11:52.420 --> 00:11:57.270
The continual convergence in the
server space toward thinner and

00:11:57.270 --> 00:12:02.470
thinner servers is causing changes
in the way systems are racked.

00:12:02.480 --> 00:12:05.860
We tend to see a lot more systems
put into a smaller amount of space,

00:12:05.860 --> 00:12:08.660
more room for cable routing
and things become very,

00:12:08.670 --> 00:12:09.760
very important.

00:12:09.760 --> 00:12:12.620
Now with Xserve,
we've designed it to provide a pretty

00:12:12.620 --> 00:12:15.800
wide range of racking capabilities,
but the reality is it's

00:12:15.800 --> 00:12:17.780
a 28-deep-inch enclosure.

00:12:17.780 --> 00:12:22.150
We recommend a 30- or deeper-inch
rack if you're doing a four-post rack.

00:12:22.420 --> 00:12:25.440
It does support two-post racks,
of course, with Xserve RAID.

00:12:25.440 --> 00:12:28.520
Not exactly something you'll
mount in a two-post rack at

00:12:28.520 --> 00:12:31.490
about 100 pounds a piece,
so really four-post

00:12:31.490 --> 00:12:33.140
racks are ideal for that.

00:12:34.580 --> 00:12:37.440
and of course we provide all the
hardware needed right in the box

00:12:37.440 --> 00:12:42.680
to mount those systems both in
English and metric threads in the box.

00:12:42.680 --> 00:12:45.180
A couple of really important
things to consider,

00:12:45.180 --> 00:12:49.420
even more so with XServe G5 is
that we're moving a tremendous

00:12:49.420 --> 00:12:50.700
amount of air through the system.

00:12:50.700 --> 00:12:56.240
XServe G5 we've doubled the CFM through
the box than the XServe G4 is.

00:12:56.240 --> 00:12:58.360
So a pure front to back
air flow is really,

00:12:58.360 --> 00:12:59.540
really important.

00:13:00.240 --> 00:13:02.830
You don't want to put too many
units in small racks like this

00:13:02.830 --> 00:13:04.300
that have an enclosed front.

00:13:04.300 --> 00:13:07.400
You want to make sure you have proper
air flow coming in through the front of

00:13:07.400 --> 00:13:09.040
the machine and out through the back.

00:13:09.080 --> 00:13:10.860
That becomes really, really important.

00:13:10.860 --> 00:13:14.350
The other thing,
if you're planning deployments with PDUs,

00:13:14.350 --> 00:13:17.660
power distribution units
going up the back of the rack,

00:13:17.660 --> 00:13:19.620
you really want to look at deeper racks.

00:13:19.620 --> 00:13:23.170
The new kind of data center
trend is becoming moving

00:13:23.170 --> 00:13:25.800
from 30 to 36 inches deep.

00:13:25.800 --> 00:13:28.720
These tend to be the more popular
racks you see in data centers

00:13:28.740 --> 00:13:30.220
that are being put in now.

00:13:30.220 --> 00:13:34.580
And those have the extra room you
might need for PDU deployment.

00:13:34.580 --> 00:13:38.490
The other thing that's important to
begin to think about if you're deploying

00:13:38.490 --> 00:13:40.410
more than a few of these is weight.

00:13:40.420 --> 00:13:44.480
XServe itself is, you know,
it's a dense server.

00:13:44.480 --> 00:13:46.140
It's about 30 pounds a pop.

00:13:46.140 --> 00:13:48.760
But when you put a lot
of these in a rack,

00:13:48.840 --> 00:13:53.470
that's a lot of pounds per square
foot that you need to think about.

00:13:53.480 --> 00:13:56.750
And if you add XServe RAIDs to that,
that even adds more

00:13:56.750 --> 00:13:58.420
weight per square foot.

00:14:00.130 --> 00:14:02.260
At Apple,
we have a cluster that we're installing.

00:14:02.260 --> 00:14:04.960
It's a 32-node cluster in our
executive briefing center.

00:14:04.960 --> 00:14:07.040
It's in a single rack.

00:14:07.040 --> 00:14:09.800
And when we met with the facilities
people about installing it,

00:14:09.800 --> 00:14:12.790
the first thing they had to do is pull
out the blueprints of the building

00:14:12.790 --> 00:14:15.940
and make sure we were over a beam
so that the floor could support it.

00:14:15.960 --> 00:14:19.020
It's actually something that
you might not think about.

00:14:19.020 --> 00:14:22.100
But with the densities that
are happening in servers today,

00:14:22.100 --> 00:14:24.280
that becomes an interesting thought.

00:14:24.280 --> 00:14:27.080
There's a great section.

00:14:27.080 --> 00:14:30.040
One of the kind of bibles for enterprise.

00:14:30.040 --> 00:14:32.770
Enterprise data center planning
is actually a book by Sun called

00:14:32.770 --> 00:14:34.700
Sun Enterprise Data Center Methodology.

00:14:34.720 --> 00:14:36.360
It's in their blueprint series.

00:14:36.360 --> 00:14:39.280
And they talk about planning
for server deployments.

00:14:39.280 --> 00:14:42.480
And they tell a story
about bringing in an E10K,

00:14:42.480 --> 00:14:45.480
which is their big kind
of mainframe SMP box.

00:14:45.480 --> 00:14:48.210
And it weighs a couple thousand pounds.

00:14:48.220 --> 00:14:51.200
And they say if you wouldn't drive
a BMW 3 Series up on top of the

00:14:51.200 --> 00:14:53.970
race floor in your data center,
you wouldn't want to bring

00:14:53.970 --> 00:14:55.280
one of these boxes in.

00:14:55.280 --> 00:14:57.920
So it's the kind of things that
you probably don't think about the

00:14:57.920 --> 00:14:59.470
floor being able to support this.

00:14:59.480 --> 00:15:00.020
But it's a great book.

00:15:00.020 --> 00:15:03.870
is something that starts to
need to be thought about.

00:15:05.820 --> 00:15:09.510
The other thing that kind of goes along
with racking is good cable management.

00:15:09.510 --> 00:15:11.900
And again, with the density and the
airflow requirements,

00:15:11.900 --> 00:15:15.660
these all go hand in hand
with good cable management.

00:15:15.660 --> 00:15:18.490
This is a picture of
an XServe deployment,

00:15:18.490 --> 00:15:20.940
not exactly fully cable managed.

00:15:20.940 --> 00:15:25.940
Another little story,
I was talking to a customer who had

00:15:25.940 --> 00:15:29.860
installed the cable management arms in
the back of their machine and saw that

00:15:29.860 --> 00:15:34.610
the airflow or the machines ran cooler
when the cables were properly managed.

00:15:34.620 --> 00:15:38.030
And they thought for sure the cable
management arm was part of the

00:15:38.030 --> 00:15:39.940
cooling solution of the XServe.

00:15:39.940 --> 00:15:41.830
And actually,
it just turns out to be a benefit

00:15:41.830 --> 00:15:44.370
of improved cable management,
being able to have air flow

00:15:44.370 --> 00:15:45.980
through the system much better.

00:15:45.980 --> 00:15:49.710
So keep in mind, cable management is an
important aspect of that.

00:15:49.710 --> 00:15:54.120
You don't want to be blocking a lot of
rear panel room with cables and things.

00:15:54.120 --> 00:15:57.700
And with multiple network cables and
power cables and fiber channel cables and

00:15:57.870 --> 00:16:01.180
all the other cables that you might be
running out of the back of the machine,

00:16:01.180 --> 00:16:03.070
in a one-use space,
that's a lot of cables

00:16:03.070 --> 00:16:04.530
that need to go somewhere.

00:16:04.620 --> 00:16:09.500
So, again, good racking also means
good cable management.

00:16:10.300 --> 00:16:12.040
The other thing is just kind
of the core requirements.

00:16:12.040 --> 00:16:14.330
Now, I'll reference you to a
knowledge base article.

00:16:14.360 --> 00:16:17.120
We publish all this information
in our knowledge base.

00:16:17.120 --> 00:16:20.270
If you go to info.apple.com
and search for Xserve and BT,

00:16:20.270 --> 00:16:23.880
you'll see all this data published
there in kind of gory detail.

00:16:25.340 --> 00:16:28.820
Xserve is very,
very efficient in its power and cooling,

00:16:28.820 --> 00:16:30.310
but yet you do need to account for it.

00:16:30.310 --> 00:16:33.870
These are some numbers for the
various Xserve configurations.

00:16:33.870 --> 00:16:37.940
We provide numbers based on stock
configuration as well as fully loaded.

00:16:37.940 --> 00:16:42.470
Fully loaded meaning, you know,
three hard drives running full

00:16:42.500 --> 00:16:45.240
complement of memory in the system.

00:16:45.240 --> 00:16:50.220
And you can see numbers anywhere
from about 130 watts to somewhere in

00:16:50.220 --> 00:16:54.100
the 290 watts of power consumption.

00:16:54.120 --> 00:16:55.300
And so, you know, it's a lot of work.

00:16:55.300 --> 00:17:01.260
It's somewhere between 400 to 900 BTUs an
hour in that range of power consumption

00:17:01.260 --> 00:17:04.120
and heat output calculated by the Xserve.

00:17:04.120 --> 00:17:07.250
The power supply is
officially rated at 4 amps,

00:17:07.250 --> 00:17:12.010
although in typical usage considerations,
you'll have a hard time finding

00:17:12.010 --> 00:17:16.090
it go above about 2.2 amps in
real-world power consumption

00:17:16.090 --> 00:17:18.610
after you bypass startup current.

00:17:18.620 --> 00:17:20.840
As a matter of fact,
the compute node is very,

00:17:20.840 --> 00:17:24.600
very efficient for the compute power
it delivers at full processor load.

00:17:25.280 --> 00:17:27.270
memory since that system
tends to be configured really

00:17:27.270 --> 00:17:28.980
just as processor in memory.

00:17:29.070 --> 00:17:33.240
You know, 1.8 amps is pretty,
pretty common for that system.

00:17:33.240 --> 00:17:37.980
So all this information we publish
very explicitly in our knowledge base,

00:17:37.980 --> 00:17:41.910
and I'll point you to
that for further details.

00:17:42.590 --> 00:17:44.730
Let's take a look now
at system configuration.

00:17:44.740 --> 00:17:45.990
How do I configure these systems?

00:17:45.990 --> 00:17:48.400
What kind of things
should I be considering?

00:17:48.400 --> 00:17:51.810
Pretty common things,
but one of the first and most basic

00:17:51.810 --> 00:17:53.850
things is how many processors.

00:17:53.880 --> 00:17:58.100
So when we sell our systems,
we have two main server configurations,

00:17:58.100 --> 00:18:00.800
a single processor and a dual processor.

00:18:00.800 --> 00:18:03.200
There's some memory
differences between the two,

00:18:03.200 --> 00:18:06.630
but the real differentiation between
the two systems and the two price

00:18:06.630 --> 00:18:08.470
points is number of processors.

00:18:08.960 --> 00:18:11.360
And since the processors
aren't upgradable later,

00:18:11.360 --> 00:18:14.250
that's one of the first decisions
that you'll have to make.

00:18:14.260 --> 00:18:17.500
Now, what's interesting about the G5
is it has so much performance.

00:18:17.520 --> 00:18:21.960
The single processor system now can
solve a much broader range of tasks.

00:18:21.980 --> 00:18:25.640
It's actually a very,
very powerful system for general

00:18:25.640 --> 00:18:27.800
purpose server activities.

00:18:27.800 --> 00:18:31.250
What's interesting, though,
is I've talked to a lot of customers

00:18:31.250 --> 00:18:35.960
who begin migrating from older servers,
particular G3s or early G4 models,

00:18:35.960 --> 00:18:37.840
up to Xserve G5s.

00:18:37.900 --> 00:18:40.060
And they're being able
to consolidate systems.

00:18:40.060 --> 00:18:44.450
You know, three or four blue and
white G3s into one Xserve.

00:18:44.460 --> 00:18:47.170
And so, you know, having the processing
power to back that up,

00:18:47.170 --> 00:18:49.640
the storage throughput,
the networking throughput,

00:18:49.640 --> 00:18:52.180
compared to what those
systems are capable of,

00:18:52.180 --> 00:18:54.060
you have that flexibility.

00:18:54.060 --> 00:18:57.670
And, again, since we can't add a
second processor later,

00:18:57.670 --> 00:19:00.710
for situations where you
want that flexibility,

00:19:00.720 --> 00:19:05.980
that freedom of growth later, you know,
having that second processor is ideal.

00:19:05.980 --> 00:19:07.840
The other thing is.

00:19:07.840 --> 00:19:09.440
You know, the storage.

00:19:09.440 --> 00:19:11.720
Now, Xserve G5,
one of the differences between

00:19:11.720 --> 00:19:14.440
that and the G4 is a change
from four drives to three.

00:19:14.440 --> 00:19:18.990
And that was done mainly to improve air
flow and meet the thermal requirements

00:19:18.990 --> 00:19:21.440
that we had to meet for the Xserve G5.

00:19:21.440 --> 00:19:25.340
Now, the implications are that with
the larger serial ATA drives

00:19:25.340 --> 00:19:28.310
that we're working with,
the actual net capacity

00:19:28.310 --> 00:19:30.440
is still 750 gigabytes.

00:19:30.440 --> 00:19:34.440
You know, nearly three-quarters of a
terabyte in a one U form factor.

00:19:34.440 --> 00:19:36.440
There's actually a tremendous
amount of storage there.

00:19:36.440 --> 00:19:37.640
What it really changes, though.

00:19:37.640 --> 00:19:40.460
Is the way you deploy
your RAID configurations.

00:19:40.520 --> 00:19:45.220
So, with software RAID built in,
you can do mirroring and

00:19:45.220 --> 00:19:48.170
striping built into the system.

00:19:48.220 --> 00:19:51.180
And we'll talk more about
RAID in a little bit.

00:19:51.260 --> 00:19:55.620
And then we offer 80 gigabyte
hard drives for basic boot drives.

00:19:55.650 --> 00:19:58.880
And so, between three drives,
you have a number of configurations.

00:19:58.880 --> 00:20:00.650
And, of course,
you always have the ability

00:20:00.650 --> 00:20:02.820
to go out the back through
fiber channel to XServe RAID,

00:20:02.820 --> 00:20:04.680
which gives you a lot more flexibility.

00:20:04.680 --> 00:20:06.570
You have more RAID level options.

00:20:06.590 --> 00:20:07.220
More capacity options.

00:20:07.220 --> 00:20:09.220
A lot of flexibility
through fiber channel.

00:20:09.220 --> 00:20:11.220
The ability to add
XSAN initially or later on.

00:20:11.220 --> 00:20:15.270
And, of course,
one of the big benefits is you can

00:20:15.270 --> 00:20:20.500
have with XServe RAID is you can
have multiple servers attaching

00:20:20.500 --> 00:20:23.220
to the same XServe RAID unit.

00:20:23.270 --> 00:20:27.710
So, as a simple example here,
we have four XServes connecting through

00:20:27.710 --> 00:20:31.530
a fiber channel switch to a single
XServe RAID that we've partitioned and

00:20:31.790 --> 00:20:36.220
sliced so that each has their own little
private volume on a shared XServe RAID.

00:20:36.220 --> 00:20:36.800
So, again, for the XServe RAID,
we have a lot of flexibility.

00:20:36.860 --> 00:20:40.450
So, again, for certain levels of storage,
this might actually be a better

00:20:40.520 --> 00:20:43.800
solution than stuffing more
storage inside an XServe itself.

00:20:43.800 --> 00:20:46.380
As a matter of fact,
having independence of your data

00:20:46.380 --> 00:20:49.660
independent of the server itself
gives you tremendous flexibility

00:20:49.800 --> 00:20:53.190
as you redeploy servers,
change their roles, migrate services from

00:20:53.200 --> 00:20:54.790
one server to another.

00:20:54.800 --> 00:20:58.800
This gives you tremendous flexibility
as you look at those options.

00:20:58.800 --> 00:21:02.790
I also wanted to talk a little bit
about the cluster node configuration.

00:21:02.800 --> 00:21:03.140
Now, as I mentioned up front,
the cluster node configuration

00:21:03.140 --> 00:21:03.470
was really -- I think it was a
little bit more complicated than

00:21:03.480 --> 00:21:03.790
it was in the previous slides.

00:21:03.800 --> 00:21:03.800
But it was a little bit more complicated
than it was in the previous slides.

00:21:03.800 --> 00:21:04.240
So, again, for certain levels of storage,
this might actually be a better

00:21:04.310 --> 00:21:04.780
solution than stuffing more
storage inside an XServe itself.

00:21:04.800 --> 00:21:08.430
So, again, as I mentioned up front,
the cluster node configuration

00:21:08.430 --> 00:21:11.780
was really designed and tailored
for compute applications.

00:21:11.800 --> 00:21:15.100
You know, traditional clusters,
high-performance computing

00:21:15.100 --> 00:21:16.800
clusters and things like that.

00:21:16.800 --> 00:21:20.650
But what's interesting is that it
does have a role for other kind

00:21:20.650 --> 00:21:22.800
of roles beyond just clusters.

00:21:22.900 --> 00:21:24.960
You know,
keeping in mind that the compute

00:21:24.960 --> 00:21:27.840
node is a dual processor system
with a single hard drive,

00:21:27.840 --> 00:21:31.790
it becomes really interesting as kind
of the appliance version of XServe.

00:21:31.820 --> 00:21:33.800
It's really great for static services
like things like VPN servers.

00:21:33.800 --> 00:21:35.800
Network services.

00:21:35.800 --> 00:21:38.500
Things where you don't need storage,
but you might want the processing

00:21:38.500 --> 00:21:40.800
power and the networking
capability that it provides.

00:21:40.800 --> 00:21:44.460
Now, one thing you do have to keep
in mind is that it ships with

00:21:44.500 --> 00:21:46.800
a 10-user license in Mac OS X.

00:21:46.800 --> 00:21:48.520
So, you know,
you're probably not going to

00:21:48.520 --> 00:21:49.800
deploy this as a file server.

00:21:49.800 --> 00:21:51.790
And it's really not the role there.

00:21:51.800 --> 00:21:54.350
And by the time you add that license,
you may decide just to go up to

00:21:54.360 --> 00:21:55.790
the full server configuration.

00:21:55.820 --> 00:22:01.070
But for a number of other applications,
especially network services,

00:22:01.070 --> 00:22:06.150
application services,
where the limitation on the number of

00:22:06.250 --> 00:22:09.340
file user connections has no impact,
all the other OS X services

00:22:09.340 --> 00:22:10.740
are fully unlimited.

00:22:10.860 --> 00:22:13.770
So, again,
I use -- this is a great VPN server,

00:22:13.770 --> 00:22:14.800
for example.

00:22:14.800 --> 00:22:17.800
And the 10-user license has no
impact on that kind of role.

00:22:17.800 --> 00:22:22.010
So that's something also that you can
keep in mind because you can get a

00:22:22.070 --> 00:22:24.800
dual processor system for a lot lower
price and take advantage of that.

00:22:24.800 --> 00:22:28.700
and take advantage of those
features if it's appropriate.

00:22:29.730 --> 00:22:32.900
The other thing about these
systems is that you have

00:22:32.910 --> 00:22:34.810
much greater RAM capability.

00:22:34.810 --> 00:22:38.300
And for applications that
really appreciate RAM,

00:22:38.300 --> 00:22:41.560
you have a lot more
headroom in the Xserve G5.

00:22:41.560 --> 00:22:45.160
With Panther Server, again,
we can put up to 8 gigabytes of RAM.

00:22:45.160 --> 00:22:47.960
It's ECC RAM,
so you have that protection there.

00:22:47.960 --> 00:22:54.480
And for applications that will
take advantage of that RAM,

00:22:54.480 --> 00:22:57.680
you have that capability.

00:22:58.300 --> 00:23:01.510
And of course, with Tiger Server,
being able to bring 64-bit

00:23:01.510 --> 00:23:04.660
user space applications and to
allocate much larger memory,

00:23:04.660 --> 00:23:08.460
we get even more capabilities as
we look down the road toward Tiger.

00:23:21.550 --> 00:23:24.360
Another thing I want to talk a
little bit about is networking.

00:23:24.410 --> 00:23:29.030
Now with Xserve G5,
we now have dual copper gigabit Ethernet

00:23:29.030 --> 00:23:30.640
ports right on the back of the machine.

00:23:30.640 --> 00:23:35.370
They're very high performance
gigabit Ethernet ports with

00:23:35.450 --> 00:23:37.940
a number of key capabilities.

00:23:37.940 --> 00:23:40.070
They have very large packet buffers.

00:23:40.070 --> 00:23:42.470
They have the ability to do jumbo frames.

00:23:42.490 --> 00:23:48.900
We've added VLAN capabilities into the
operating system for VLAN operations.

00:23:48.900 --> 00:23:54.780
And so the bandwidth that we're able
to provide out of the machine is much,

00:23:54.780 --> 00:23:55.400
much greater.

00:23:55.400 --> 00:23:58.100
And of course,
you can add multiple port Ethernet cards.

00:23:58.100 --> 00:24:00.130
We have a single port
available from Apple,

00:24:00.130 --> 00:24:02.500
multiple port cards from
other third parties.

00:24:02.500 --> 00:24:06.920
SmallTree Communications in particular
has a number of cards that are available.

00:24:06.920 --> 00:24:13.670
And so we're very excited to
see that coming to Tiger is

00:24:13.670 --> 00:24:17.490
network link aggregation.

00:24:17.490 --> 00:24:21.460
So you'll see that in Tiger Server.

00:24:23.300 --> 00:24:26.640
I think that's going to give you
a lot more bandwidth out of XServe

00:24:26.640 --> 00:24:30.300
G5 and be able to take these two
ports and provide more bandwidth.

00:24:30.300 --> 00:24:33.300
And of course you can also configure
it in a failover configuration.

00:24:33.460 --> 00:24:38.200
So that will be available to you
when Tiger Server is available.

00:24:38.300 --> 00:24:43.300
Of course that solution is available
today for Panther from a third party.

00:24:43.320 --> 00:24:46.300
SmallTree also has that
software as an add-on.

00:24:46.300 --> 00:24:48.440
So for people looking
for that capability now,

00:24:48.440 --> 00:24:51.770
you do have a way to add that
on to the operating system.

00:24:53.470 --> 00:24:56.690
And finally, a number of options that are
available directly from Apple,

00:24:56.690 --> 00:25:01.090
most particularly some
of the new I/O cards,

00:25:01.110 --> 00:25:05.290
PCIX SCSI card, for example,
dual channel Ultra 320 card,

00:25:05.290 --> 00:25:09.030
particularly handy for SCSI-based
raids that you may have in

00:25:09.030 --> 00:25:13.060
your architecture already,
and also very popular for

00:25:13.060 --> 00:25:15.670
backup devices in particular.

