saving Word files occasionally is
a lot different from a user moving,

00:26:38.630 --> 00:26:42.030
you know, 40 gigabyte Photoshop images
back and forth.

00:26:42.040 --> 00:26:45.130
With home directories becoming
more and more popular,

00:26:45.130 --> 00:26:47.920
that also has a little
higher load on the server,

00:26:47.920 --> 00:26:53.040
and that's something to
calculate into in mind as well.

00:26:53.040 --> 00:26:56.930
Also, the move toward more centralized
directory services is something

00:26:56.930 --> 00:27:00.080
to take a look at as you're
setting up directory servers.

00:27:00.080 --> 00:27:02.040
The number of users who are online.

00:27:02.420 --> 00:27:07.090
authenticating concurrently become a
factor that you need to take a look at.

00:27:07.890 --> 00:27:11.760
What's interesting with XServe G5 is
that we've seen some pretty phenomenal

00:27:11.760 --> 00:27:13.800
scalability on Netboot servers.

00:27:13.800 --> 00:27:20.330
We've seen the ability to put a lot
higher number of machines on Netboot and

00:27:20.330 --> 00:27:22.660
some tests that we've been able to do.

00:27:22.660 --> 00:27:25.670
Still, that depends heavily on the
level of performance and the

00:27:25.670 --> 00:27:27.620
networking that you're looking for.

00:27:27.620 --> 00:27:32.500
But we've had deployments where
we've put as many as 150 iMac

00:27:32.550 --> 00:27:34.840
clients on a single XServe.

00:27:34.840 --> 00:27:37.740
And not that that's a
recommended configuration,

00:27:37.740 --> 00:27:41.830
but to know that it scales
that high is pretty phenomenal.

00:27:41.840 --> 00:27:44.400
The other thing is QuickTime streaming.

00:27:44.400 --> 00:27:48.150
QuickTime streaming is another one where
you really need to be able to look at

00:27:48.150 --> 00:27:52.070
the size of media that you're streaming,
the bandwidth that

00:27:52.070 --> 00:27:54.320
you're able to provide.

00:27:54.510 --> 00:27:58.410
You're almost always limited by the
network bandwidth outgoing before the

00:27:58.410 --> 00:28:00.980
server will be the limiting factor.

00:28:02.160 --> 00:28:04.910
So let's move on and talk a
little bit more about deployment.

00:28:04.940 --> 00:28:08.490
So we've moved from planning
on to actual deployment.

00:28:09.290 --> 00:28:13.380
So again, kind of the first thing is,
again, looking at the most common uses

00:28:13.380 --> 00:28:15.420
that Xserve is deployed upon.

00:28:15.420 --> 00:28:18.840
And again, if you look at the list,
these are the services that are, again,

00:28:18.840 --> 00:28:21.080
built right into Mac OS X Server.

00:28:21.080 --> 00:28:24.980
You know, the interesting thing about
this class of server is that,

00:28:24.980 --> 00:28:28.440
you know, by far the most typical uses
are things like file and print,

00:28:28.440 --> 00:28:32.600
network services, mail services,
web services, email services.

00:28:32.600 --> 00:28:34.920
And we just have phenomenal
network services built right

00:28:34.920 --> 00:28:36.240
into the operating system.

00:28:36.940 --> 00:28:40.270
And this is, of course,
some of the most popular

00:28:40.270 --> 00:28:42.630
deployments used with Xserve.

00:28:44.390 --> 00:28:47.340
A couple of important things.

00:28:47.340 --> 00:28:51.170
I get asked a lot about
software installation when

00:28:51.170 --> 00:28:52.540
you get a brand new Xserve.

00:28:52.540 --> 00:28:55.520
Do I need to go ahead and
reformat it right out of the box?

00:28:55.520 --> 00:29:00.070
The configuration that ships in the
factory after the whole factory process

00:29:00.080 --> 00:29:04.410
is actually the exact same thing
that you get right on the hard drive.

00:29:04.420 --> 00:29:07.190
But the reality is most system
administrators really prefer to

00:29:07.190 --> 00:29:10.340
reload the operating system and
know exactly how it's configured.

00:29:11.060 --> 00:29:14.690
The other thing is the impact of having
to reconfigure the drives for the

00:29:14.710 --> 00:29:19.230
software RAID levels that you're looking
for will require reinstallation as well.

00:29:19.240 --> 00:29:22.720
We're going to talk a little bit
about headless administration and

00:29:22.730 --> 00:29:25.940
setup assistant in just a minute.

00:29:25.970 --> 00:29:30.520
But with the remote setup tools,
you actually have a very robust way to

00:29:30.520 --> 00:29:36.020
completely setup and get your server
right out of the box without ever needing

00:29:36.020 --> 00:29:38.300
to hook up a keyboard and a monitor.

00:29:38.320 --> 00:29:39.720
And these are tools that we've
worked really hard to make sure

00:29:39.720 --> 00:29:40.440
that we're able to do that.

00:29:40.490 --> 00:29:40.820
Thank you.

00:29:40.820 --> 00:29:45.840
And of course,
software update provides an easy

00:29:45.890 --> 00:29:52.820
way to get your server up to date
with the latest security updates,

00:29:52.820 --> 00:29:56.060
software updates that are
available directly from Apple.

00:29:58.670 --> 00:30:02.820
The other thing is when you're
deploying multiple servers,

00:30:02.820 --> 00:30:06.600
it's very common to image a single server
and clone that onto other machines.

00:30:06.800 --> 00:30:08.570
With the removable
drive modules built in,

00:30:08.570 --> 00:30:11.100
that becomes really,
really easy with the capabilities

00:30:11.100 --> 00:30:12.600
right in the operating system.

00:30:12.600 --> 00:30:17.600
And of course with front panel target
disk mode being available to you,

00:30:17.600 --> 00:30:20.600
you can literally just with a short
firewire cable clone one complete

00:30:20.600 --> 00:30:24.400
server installation to a second server
right using front panel firewire.

00:30:24.400 --> 00:30:27.390
So that becomes very handy.

00:30:27.680 --> 00:30:31.590
So speaking of front panel mode,
I wanted to provide a

00:30:31.630 --> 00:30:32.720
latest update on this.

00:30:32.720 --> 00:30:36.390
One of the new capabilities in Xserve G5,
we've actually added a new

00:30:36.390 --> 00:30:38.200
capability to the front panel mode.

00:30:38.230 --> 00:30:41.650
So by holding down the front panel
button on the system identifier

00:30:41.710 --> 00:30:44.820
button on the front of Xserve,
we can perform almost all the

00:30:44.820 --> 00:30:48.570
operations you used to be able to
perform by holding down special keys,

00:30:48.570 --> 00:30:53.020
snag keys, zapping the PRAM,
target disk mode, things like that.

00:30:53.500 --> 00:30:58.460
This is also referenced in a knowledge
base article on our website as well.

00:30:58.460 --> 00:31:02.170
So obviously things like net
boot and capabilities like that,

00:31:02.170 --> 00:31:05.140
boot from CD,
target disk mode are available.

00:31:05.140 --> 00:31:08.230
You'll see though on Xserve
G5 we added a new one,

00:31:08.280 --> 00:31:09.600
option number 8.

00:31:09.600 --> 00:31:12.930
We reserved that one for
future use and this is it.

00:31:12.930 --> 00:31:16.890
We've added a diagnostics mode
built right into the Xserve.

00:31:16.900 --> 00:31:21.130
And so by selecting a diagnostics mode,
you can actually have the

00:31:21.130 --> 00:31:23.430
system boot up over the network.

00:31:23.500 --> 00:31:27.580
So we've added a new one called
Xserve Remote Diagnostics.

00:31:27.580 --> 00:31:32.300
It's a new feature on Xserve G5
called Xserve Remote Diagnostics.

00:31:32.300 --> 00:31:37.520
And it's particularly handy if you
have a larger installation of Xserves.

00:31:37.520 --> 00:31:40.800
What you need to do is
set up a net boot server,

00:31:40.890 --> 00:31:45.720
turn on the net boot feature,
and put the diagnostics and activate

00:31:45.720 --> 00:31:48.990
the diagnostics image on that Xserve.

00:31:49.300 --> 00:31:54.880
and David The diagnostics tools are
based directly on the tools we use in the

00:31:54.880 --> 00:31:56.900
factory when testing our own machines.

00:31:56.900 --> 00:32:03.200
They're extremely thorough and some of
the most robust tests that are available.

00:32:03.200 --> 00:32:04.380
As a matter of fact,
some of the tests that we use

00:32:04.490 --> 00:32:09.180
for testing the CPU and the
memory are absolutely phenomenal.

00:32:09.180 --> 00:32:12.650
There have been papers written on
the algorithms used that we use

00:32:12.650 --> 00:32:14.780
to do things like testing memory.

00:32:14.780 --> 00:32:17.930
And so those tests are available
to you now directly through

00:32:17.930 --> 00:32:19.940
these remote diagnostics tools.

00:32:19.940 --> 00:32:22.520
And so by holding down the front panel,
you can put the machine

00:32:22.520 --> 00:32:24.000
into a diagnostics mode.

00:32:24.000 --> 00:32:27.690
If this machine's in a known running
state and you just want to test it,

00:32:27.690 --> 00:32:31.360
by using the command line tool,
you can go in and activate it

00:32:31.360 --> 00:32:34.550
and it will boot in diagnostics
mode and then return to the known

00:32:34.560 --> 00:32:36.560
operating system when complete.

00:32:36.560 --> 00:32:40.260
If it is in an unknown state, you know,
you've got a machine,

00:32:40.260 --> 00:32:43.610
you don't know if it's working right,
doesn't seem to be booting right,

00:32:43.670 --> 00:32:46.300
you can use that front
panel mode to trigger it.

00:32:46.330 --> 00:32:50.860
And then trigger this from a machine
on your same subnet to run the client

00:32:50.860 --> 00:32:53.500
to run those diagnostics tools.

00:32:53.500 --> 00:32:55.470
What's really interesting
about these tools is that

00:32:55.470 --> 00:32:57.490
there's a configuration file.

00:32:57.550 --> 00:33:01.150
We provide out of the
box two diagnostic tests,

00:33:01.150 --> 00:33:03.520
a short test and a long test.

00:33:03.520 --> 00:33:08.880
And one's kind of a quick peek at the key
functions and one's a much deeper test.

00:33:08.880 --> 00:33:12.010
These are text files that you can
configure and you can configure

00:33:12.010 --> 00:33:13.840
these to run very specific tests.

00:33:13.840 --> 00:33:16.040
If you're really interesting,
you've got a new batch of memory,

00:33:16.040 --> 00:33:17.380
you can run a new batch of memory
and you just want to run the

00:33:17.380 --> 00:33:21.320
memory tests over and over to
test the integrity of your memory.

00:33:21.320 --> 00:33:23.150
You have that ability just
to help tell the test,

00:33:23.160 --> 00:33:26.640
create a custom file that runs just
memory tests and really burn that

00:33:26.640 --> 00:33:29.220
memory in as you've added to the system.

00:33:29.220 --> 00:33:31.880
So very flexible and this is
something that we are really

00:33:32.070 --> 00:33:33.640
excited to get into the system.

00:33:35.890 --> 00:33:39.350
So, I wanted to talk a little bit
more about remote management

00:33:39.400 --> 00:33:40.930
and headless operations.

00:33:41.190 --> 00:33:43.980
One of the big things that we
did with the XServe G5 is that

00:33:44.240 --> 00:33:46.320
we made the video card optional.

00:33:46.350 --> 00:33:50.800
And there's been a little
bit of issue with that.

00:33:50.970 --> 00:33:55.880
People who are used to having that
video card there in the XServe G4.

00:33:56.160 --> 00:33:59.140
This is something that we've been working
to and we're finally at the point where

00:33:59.140 --> 00:34:03.530
we believe the remote management tools
are really robust enough to give you

00:34:03.530 --> 00:34:06.300
a number of ways to manage the system.

00:34:06.400 --> 00:34:08.360
Now,
obviously for people who want the video

00:34:08.360 --> 00:34:10.340
card and want to be able to use it,
for example,

00:34:10.340 --> 00:34:13.890
if KVM switches on your network,
it's an easy option

00:34:13.890 --> 00:34:15.570
to add to your system.

00:34:15.650 --> 00:34:18.800
But we've also worked very hard on
things like the remote management tools,

00:34:18.800 --> 00:34:22.240
the remote setup assistant to make
sure that you can do everything that

00:34:22.240 --> 00:34:24.940
you need to do through those tools.

00:34:24.940 --> 00:34:27.370
So, out of the box,
you have the ability without ever

00:34:27.380 --> 00:34:30.730
hooking up a keyboard or a mouse
to be able to rack the system,

00:34:30.730 --> 00:34:34.060
power it up on your network
and set it up remotely.

00:34:34.060 --> 00:34:36.300
So,
that's a really good way to get started.

00:34:36.300 --> 00:34:39.240
And then, of course,
you can also use the remote setup tools.

00:34:39.240 --> 00:34:41.060
As a matter of fact,
with some of the new capabilities

00:34:41.060 --> 00:34:43.980
that were introduced last
year in Panther Server,

00:34:43.980 --> 00:34:47.040
you can take advantage of
tools like auto server setup,

00:34:47.040 --> 00:34:50.820
where from a configuration file
either on a thing like an iPod,

00:34:50.820 --> 00:34:54.140
a USB key, or even an LDAP server,
if you're setting up a

00:34:54.160 --> 00:34:57.110
large number of machines,
the machines can go to

00:34:57.110 --> 00:35:01.750
that reference file,
configure themselves automatically,

00:35:02.200 --> 00:35:05.820
The other thing that becomes interesting
is Apple Remote Desktop for that

00:35:05.820 --> 00:35:09.500
remote screen sharing presence
where you want to really have that

00:35:09.500 --> 00:35:13.000
GUI management perspective but
want to be able to hit it remotely.

00:35:13.000 --> 00:35:16.930
Apple Remote Desktop really
becomes a great tool to use here,

00:35:16.940 --> 00:35:20.460
especially the new version of
Apple Remote Desktop version 2.

00:35:20.460 --> 00:35:22.660
It gives you a number
of new capabilities.

00:35:22.660 --> 00:35:25.000
You can almost think of this
as a virtual KVM switch.

00:35:25.000 --> 00:35:28.180
So from a PowerBook anywhere,
you can connect remotely into

00:35:28.180 --> 00:35:29.760
your XServe and manage it.

00:35:30.230 --> 00:35:32.040
As a matter of fact,
with the VNC capabilities,

00:35:32.040 --> 00:35:38.160
you could even manage your XServe with
a GUI session from a PC running VNC.

00:35:38.160 --> 00:35:40.000
So this becomes very, very powerful.

00:35:40.000 --> 00:35:44.620
That plus the ability to run shell
scripts and push out software to a

00:35:44.620 --> 00:35:49.420
large number of machines make it a
really attractive way to manage XServes.

00:35:49.420 --> 00:35:51.280
And it's something you might
want to consider adding to

00:35:51.280 --> 00:35:52.500
your remote management tools.

00:35:52.500 --> 00:35:55.530
We'll do a demo in a little bit and
we'll be using Apple Remote Desktop.

00:35:57.650 --> 00:36:01.020
What's neat about what we've
done in the Xserve setup is we've

00:36:01.020 --> 00:36:04.160
added Apple Remote Desktop right
in the remote setup assistant.

00:36:04.210 --> 00:36:08.380
So when you're walking through the
setup tools by turning on one checkbox,

00:36:08.380 --> 00:36:12.840
you can automatically enable
Apple Remote Desktop for the system

00:36:12.840 --> 00:36:16.290
administrator user that you create when
you go through the setup assistant.

00:36:16.350 --> 00:36:19.450
So from there on out,
you can manage the system completely

00:36:19.480 --> 00:36:21.400
through Apple Remote Desktop.

00:36:22.140 --> 00:36:26.800
and of course for the command line users,
we have really made a lot of effort in

00:36:26.800 --> 00:36:30.400
Panther to add more command line tools,
to upgrade the man pages and

00:36:30.400 --> 00:36:33.890
really make command line a very
robust way to manage the system.

00:36:33.900 --> 00:36:37.440
So for command line users who
want to script and automate things

00:36:37.440 --> 00:36:40.500
and really take advantage of the
management tools at that level,

00:36:40.500 --> 00:36:44.900
that becomes a very equal
way to manage the system.

00:36:44.900 --> 00:36:49.130
As a matter of fact, a lot of people,
you might not be aware of this,

00:36:49.140 --> 00:36:51.940
but we actually provide
off our install CDs,

00:36:51.960 --> 00:36:55.690
boot CD1, when you boot up that CD,
SSH is actually enabled.

00:36:55.700 --> 00:37:01.220
So you can actually install the operating
system and manage it from the CD at

00:37:01.220 --> 00:37:04.060
that time while booted from the CD.

00:37:04.100 --> 00:37:09.250
The username is root, of course,
because it's a single user

00:37:09.250 --> 00:37:13.420
on the CD and the password,
just like the remote setup assistant,

00:37:13.430 --> 00:37:14.100
is the first eight digits of the CD.

00:37:14.100 --> 00:37:20.970
So that becomes an access method as well.

00:37:22.020 --> 00:37:27.280
I want to point out there's a phenomenal
command line administration guide that's

00:37:27.280 --> 00:37:28.700
available from the server website.

00:37:28.700 --> 00:37:33.740
And if you're a command line user and
want to know all the subtle nuances of

00:37:33.740 --> 00:37:37.950
some of the unique Mac OS X commands,
tools that might be a little bit

00:37:37.980 --> 00:37:42.290
different from other Unix distributions,
if you're coming from a Linux or

00:37:42.290 --> 00:37:45.990
a Solaris environment and want to
become adept at some of the unique

00:37:45.990 --> 00:37:49.420
tools that are available on Mac OS X,
highly recommend the command

00:37:49.420 --> 00:37:51.430
line user administration guide.

00:37:52.000 --> 00:37:54.470
It's just one of many,
many documentation pieces that we make

00:37:54.470 --> 00:37:56.320
available on our website for download.

00:37:56.320 --> 00:38:00.480
But it really goes into the
depths of the command line tools.

00:38:03.540 --> 00:38:06.580
So again,
with the remote management tools that

00:38:06.620 --> 00:38:10.560
we provide in the operating system,
server monitor for monitoring

00:38:10.560 --> 00:38:14.000
the hardware and providing
in-depth view into Xserve itself,

00:38:14.000 --> 00:38:17.980
server admin and work group manager,
all these tools can be managed

00:38:18.250 --> 00:38:20.160
remotely from another Mac OS X client.

00:38:20.160 --> 00:38:28.130
They work over an encrypted and
authenticated link and provide just

00:38:28.130 --> 00:38:28.130
a great remote management experience.

00:38:28.300 --> 00:38:31.240
So with that,
I'd like to introduce Greg Smith,

00:38:31.250 --> 00:38:35.300
who's going to come up and
help me with a demo here.

00:38:40.860 --> 00:38:45.560
So we actually have two
Xserves here on stage.

00:38:45.560 --> 00:38:48.870
And we're going to pull up
Server Monitor and take a look

00:38:48.880 --> 00:38:51.480
at some of the new values that we
make available in Server Monitor.

00:38:51.480 --> 00:38:54.360
So looking at the first server here,
we have an info tab,

00:38:54.360 --> 00:38:58.120
and we can kind of get all the
high-level information about this system.

00:38:58.120 --> 00:39:01.720
We see here that we have
a dual 2 gigahertz system.

00:39:01.720 --> 00:39:03.580
We have the serial number available.

00:39:03.580 --> 00:39:06.630
One button gets you a complete
Apple system profile report,

00:39:06.660 --> 00:39:08.940
which is a great tool
for asset management.

00:39:09.200 --> 00:39:11.530
Some of the unique things that
are in the new version for

00:39:11.530 --> 00:39:13.060
XServe G5 are the memory tab.

00:39:13.060 --> 00:39:16.760
As I mentioned, with XServe G5,
we now have ECC memory in the system.

00:39:16.760 --> 00:39:21.040
We're actually tracking ECC memory
errors by individual DIMM in the system.

00:39:21.040 --> 00:39:25.560
So should you ever see ECC error counts,
and they should almost always be zero,

00:39:25.560 --> 00:39:29.400
but you'll be able to see exactly
what DIMM is causing those problems.

00:39:29.400 --> 00:39:31.940
And, of course, they're automatically
corrected on the fly,

00:39:31.940 --> 00:39:34.100
so you don't have to
necessarily worry about them,

00:39:34.100 --> 00:39:37.090
but you'll be able to understand what's
happening with that individual DIMM.

00:39:37.780 --> 00:39:41.100
The power tab has added a tremendous
amount of more information.

00:39:41.100 --> 00:39:43.840
We have many more sensors on the board.

00:39:43.840 --> 00:39:47.360
We're able to monitor voltages of
many core ASICs in the systems,

00:39:47.360 --> 00:39:49.580
voltages coming off the power supplies.

00:39:49.600 --> 00:39:53.560
And one of the ones I really
like is the power pop-up,

00:39:53.890 --> 00:39:59.590
which provides real-time calculated
power of the two CPUs and watts.

00:39:59.600 --> 00:40:03.600
So we're able to calculate voltage
and power coming right into the CPU.

00:40:03.600 --> 00:40:06.600
So if you pull in the power supply there,
go to processor power.

00:40:07.240 --> 00:40:12.200
At the top there, Greg,
on the power supply tab, go to power.

00:40:12.200 --> 00:40:13.200
There we go.

00:40:13.200 --> 00:40:16.280
We'll actually see in real time
the wattage being consumed by the

00:40:16.280 --> 00:40:18.000
dual processors in the system.

00:40:18.000 --> 00:40:20.580
So you mentioned,
remember the earlier graph that

00:40:20.580 --> 00:40:24.900
I mentioned that the processors are
typically about 55-watt max processors.

00:40:24.900 --> 00:40:29.230
Well, in idle, as they're sitting here,
they're barely in the teens, you know,

00:40:29.240 --> 00:40:31.000
just sitting around idling.

00:40:31.000 --> 00:40:32.700
So, again, very efficient on power.

00:40:32.700 --> 00:40:36.100
Other tabs that are interesting
are the temperature tab.

00:40:36.800 --> 00:40:38.300
We have 10 temperature sensors.

00:40:38.300 --> 00:40:41.800
We can see the inlet temperatures
in the systems coming in.

00:40:41.800 --> 00:40:46.830
If you go to blowers,
we'll see the real-time fan

00:40:46.870 --> 00:40:49.800
