00:46:05.440 --> 00:46:09.930
One of the big things that we're seeing
with backup is backup continues to be

00:46:09.930 --> 00:46:12.600
a huge challenge in server deployment.

00:46:12.600 --> 00:46:15.840
The reality is that more and
more data is being kept online

00:46:15.840 --> 00:46:19.760
for a variety of reasons,
including legal compliance reasons.

00:46:21.020 --> 00:46:24.270
There's more data being shurned, right,
when you're working with large

00:46:24.360 --> 00:46:26.150
files or working with large content.

00:46:26.150 --> 00:46:28.950
The amount of data that needs
to be backed up on a delta

00:46:28.950 --> 00:46:30.680
basis is becoming much larger.

00:46:30.680 --> 00:46:35.300
And the reality is that there are no
down times in server operation anymore,

00:46:35.300 --> 00:46:35.960
right?

00:46:35.960 --> 00:46:38.670
It's a 24 by 7 internet access world.

00:46:38.670 --> 00:46:40.640
There's always someone
accessing your website,

00:46:40.660 --> 00:46:42.140
always someone accessing your data.

00:46:42.140 --> 00:46:44.960
So the fact is that the backup windows,
the opportunities for

00:46:44.960 --> 00:46:46.160
backup are shrinking.

00:46:48.150 --> 00:46:51.340
The other really hard reality is that,
and I remember years ago,

00:46:51.340 --> 00:46:54.980
I used to back up my entire
40 gig hard drive on a 40 gig,

00:46:54.980 --> 00:46:58.350
40 megabyte hard drive, excuse me,
40 megabyte hard drive on

00:46:58.350 --> 00:46:59.810
a single 40 megabyte tape.

00:46:59.850 --> 00:47:01.620
It was really easy just
to back up everything.

00:47:01.620 --> 00:47:04.910
The fact is these large,
large hard drives just aren't keeping up,

00:47:04.910 --> 00:47:08.040
or the tape capacities are just
not keeping up with these large,

00:47:08.040 --> 00:47:09.330
large hard drives.

00:47:09.720 --> 00:47:12.500
And the fact is while RAID provides
tremendous data protection,

00:47:12.500 --> 00:47:15.420
matter of fact, looking at the solutions
that we just looked at here,

00:47:15.600 --> 00:47:16.810
RAID is not backup.

00:47:16.820 --> 00:47:19.210
Even a mirror,
if you get a virus or some kind

00:47:19.210 --> 00:47:22.540
of corruption that appears,
it happens on both drives.

00:47:22.540 --> 00:47:23.660
So RAID is not backup.

00:47:25.190 --> 00:47:28.600
Great news is that we're seeing a
tremendous number of industry solutions

00:47:28.600 --> 00:47:29.940
being available on the platform.

00:47:29.940 --> 00:47:34.460
And again, if you were able to attend
the backup session today,

00:47:34.460 --> 00:47:39.740
you're seeing a number of enterprise
solutions available for anything from

00:47:39.740 --> 00:47:43.510
single server local backup to work
group backup to enterprise backup

00:47:43.510 --> 00:47:45.520
being available to you on Mac OS X.

00:47:45.520 --> 00:47:48.370
As a matter of fact,
the number of clients and server

00:47:48.370 --> 00:47:50.220
solutions continues to grow.

00:47:50.220 --> 00:47:53.620
And we're seeing more and
more options available to you.

00:47:54.400 --> 00:47:57.360
The main thing I wanted to just
touch on is the growing trend

00:47:57.360 --> 00:47:58.960
toward disk-to-disk backup.

00:47:58.960 --> 00:48:02.550
So with the capacity that our
servers are able to hold today,

00:48:02.550 --> 00:48:06.540
alternative backup strategies
are becoming very important.

00:48:06.540 --> 00:48:09.960
And being able to do things
like disk-to-disk backup,

00:48:09.960 --> 00:48:13.470
staging server backup to disk
for performance and speed

00:48:13.470 --> 00:48:17.080
and quick accessibility,
as well as adding capabilities

00:48:17.080 --> 00:48:20.660
like disk-to-disk to tape is
a trend that's not going away.

00:48:20.660 --> 00:48:22.920
We're seeing more and more
software add this capability.

00:48:23.700 --> 00:48:24.440
We're seeing more and more
software add this capability,

00:48:24.440 --> 00:48:25.140
which is becoming very, very attractive.

00:48:25.140 --> 00:48:28.550
The low price point of storage,
