very attractive for this class of backup.

00:48:33.130 --> 00:48:36.330
So it gives you a way to
provide massive backup at very,

00:48:36.340 --> 00:48:38.020
very high rates of speed.

00:48:38.020 --> 00:48:44.130
Something to consider as you look
at large backup requirements.

00:48:44.560 --> 00:48:47.490
Another thing I wanted to
touch on is high availability.

00:48:47.500 --> 00:48:49.890
If you've heard in some
of the sessions this week,

00:48:49.950 --> 00:48:53.700
Tiger Server will add some
new availability options to

00:48:53.800 --> 00:48:55.360
the server operating system.

00:48:55.360 --> 00:48:58.490
In Panther,
we continue to have IP failover

00:48:58.500 --> 00:49:03.060
capabilities to provide a script-driven
failover operation between key

00:49:03.060 --> 00:49:05.200
services running on your server.

00:49:05.200 --> 00:49:07.840
These are particularly
ideal for static services,

00:49:07.840 --> 00:49:11.130
so not things like file services,
but more things like streaming

00:49:11.160 --> 00:49:12.700
services and web services.

00:49:13.280 --> 00:49:16.840
These are built right into the operating
system and give you a great capability.

00:49:16.840 --> 00:49:19.380
If we look at it from
a diagram standpoint,

00:49:19.380 --> 00:49:23.720
you can have a master server and a backup
server with a heartbeat between the two,

00:49:23.720 --> 00:49:29.230
such that if one interface should fail,
the services would fall over

00:49:29.230 --> 00:49:31.520
to the secondary server.

00:49:31.520 --> 00:49:35.020
Because it's all script-driven,
you have the ability to reprioritize load

00:49:35.020 --> 00:49:38.780
or even terminate load that you may not
want to keep around in that situation.

00:49:38.780 --> 00:49:44.990
It gives you a very flexible way
to... to manage those services.

00:49:45.000 --> 00:49:49.550
What's interesting, our tools like rsync,
now the IP failover architecture

00:49:49.550 --> 00:49:53.420
itself doesn't move data,
but with added services like rsync,

00:49:53.460 --> 00:49:56.660
you have the ability to
replicate data between services,

00:49:56.660 --> 00:49:58.700
between servers themselves.

00:49:58.700 --> 00:50:02.770
As a fact, you can use it for two-way
replication so that you have failover

00:50:02.770 --> 00:50:06.610
both ways between two servers,
as an example here.

00:50:06.990 --> 00:50:11.220
What's also very interesting is that
